that really inspires me

00:40:35.150 --> 00:40:37.060
but not at the beginning.

00:40:37.060 --> 00:40:43.940
At the beginning for me, you
know, I come from a family and one

00:40:43.940 --> 00:40:47.090
of my cousins is here,
very close to you, Elsa,

00:40:47.090 --> 00:40:51.060
that is a family immigrated
from the North of Mexico

00:40:51.060 --> 00:40:53.940
from Sonora, from the desert.

00:40:53.940 --> 00:41:01.640
And as immigrated family
we have a lot of gatherings

00:41:01.640 --> 00:41:07.200
where the oldest first and
then every one tell stories.

00:41:07.200 --> 00:41:14.550
So, my grandmother was
a wonderful storyteller.

00:41:14.550 --> 00:41:20.240
So storytelling, when I wrote
for the first time something was

00:41:20.240 --> 00:41:24.320
because I wanted to
write something to read

00:41:24.320 --> 00:41:27.040
to my family, to tell to my family.

00:41:27.040 --> 00:41:32.350
Not only, you know, the
conversation in the dinner, really,

00:41:32.350 --> 00:41:36.080
for example the ritual do
you remember Elsa the ritual

00:41:36.080 --> 00:41:41.130
of giving gifts in
Christmas was a performance.

00:41:41.130 --> 00:41:47.000
One of the uncles came and he
invested stories when he saw

00:41:47.000 --> 00:41:51.780
who was giving to whom and he
invented the story about the people

00:41:51.780 --> 00:41:56.530
who was-- who receive the gift and
this story was very imaginative

00:41:56.530 --> 00:42:01.300
and everybody wanted to guess and
then to guess what it was inside.

00:42:01.300 --> 00:42:05.430
So, when I went to Morocco
one of the things thing

00:42:05.430 --> 00:42:11.980
that impress me was a
wonderful amazing tradition

00:42:11.980 --> 00:42:15.560
of telling stories
in the public spaces.

00:42:15.560 --> 00:42:18.000
And, you know, there is a square

00:42:18.000 --> 00:42:23.650
in Marrakech called the
square [foreign language],

00:42:23.650 --> 00:42:25.910
which means the square of the dead.

00:42:25.910 --> 00:42:29.170
And there, there is a storytellers.

00:42:29.170 --> 00:42:35.820
And the storytellers are amazingly
alive and they have rituals and I--

00:42:35.820 --> 00:42:38.370
there is a lot of anthropologies
who study them.

00:42:38.370 --> 00:42:44.150 position:56%
They have for example something that
I try to have on this books and I--

00:42:44.150 --> 00:42:47.820
when I was talking about the twos
and the readers and the people

00:42:47.820 --> 00:42:51.540
who writes me is that
they call it halqa.

00:42:51.540 --> 00:42:54.420
Halqa means the audience.

00:42:54.420 --> 00:42:58.910
The audience is that always
go surrounding one storyteller

00:42:58.910 --> 00:43:06.180
and this storyteller includes
what the audience tells them.

00:43:06.180 --> 00:43:08.440
And it becomes part of the story.

00:43:08.440 --> 00:43:14.490
And as what they tell becomes part
of the story is also the tradition.

00:43:14.490 --> 00:43:21.590
So, a lot of classics and
a lot of the literature

00:43:21.590 --> 00:43:24.900
that you can learn here in
the university but, you know,

00:43:24.900 --> 00:43:30.110
one of the nicest things I learned
on the street happen on the ship.

00:43:30.110 --> 00:43:35.240
On the ship, we went 36 hours
in the basement on that ship

00:43:35.240 --> 00:43:41.760 position:56%
and there was more than a nightmare
there was a storm and really a storm

00:43:41.760 --> 00:43:45.980 position:56%
that put everyone out of their body.

00:43:45.980 --> 00:43:52.410
Everybody was very,
very, very, very sick.

00:43:52.410 --> 00:43:58.160 position:56%
And, you know, there was cries there
was the smell, everything was--

00:43:58.160 --> 00:44:01.830
it was so strong and
so hard that you felt

00:44:01.830 --> 00:44:06.230 position:56%
that the storm didn't began outside
that came to you but the storm began

00:44:06.230 --> 00:44:12.400
in your body and was the trebling
was really projecting towards the

00:44:12.400 --> 00:44:15.850
sky that it was in your stomach
that the storm was beginning.

00:44:15.850 --> 00:44:20.310
It was really something that you
began and the ship made like that.

00:44:20.310 --> 00:44:26.780
And you couldn't sleep
of course you vanished.

00:44:26.780 --> 00:44:28.720
So we vanished.

00:44:28.720 --> 00:44:37.190
And we woke up 36 hour later
and there was a light who came

00:44:37.190 --> 00:44:42.050
to the basement and there was the
sound that said, well, you know,

00:44:42.050 --> 00:44:48.530 position:56%
first class will go down first and
we hear, [footsteps] people running.

00:44:48.530 --> 00:44:53.970
And then second class and third
class and they were already down.

00:44:53.970 --> 00:44:58.580
And fourth class, that
was us, and nobody move.

00:44:58.580 --> 00:45:03.470
So, my wife and I we were in
the floor like that so we try

00:45:03.470 --> 00:45:08.480
to see there was no one there and
all the people was in the back

00:45:08.480 --> 00:45:13.190
of the room and there was
a man telling a story.

00:45:13.190 --> 00:45:15.370
It was a storyteller.

00:45:15.370 --> 00:45:21.040
And this storyteller
was a storyteller

00:45:21.040 --> 00:45:23.130
from the [foreign language] square.

00:45:23.130 --> 00:45:27.920
And he was I notice that he
was telling what we live the

00:45:27.920 --> 00:45:29.260
life before.

00:45:29.260 --> 00:45:30.880
He was telling about us.

00:45:30.880 --> 00:45:34.930
He was telling about a woman who
wrapped a baby with his shawl

00:45:34.930 --> 00:45:37.760
and the baby was like
planet around it.

00:45:37.760 --> 00:45:41.510
There was the story of very
religious people what do you do

00:45:41.510 --> 00:45:45.130
when you are very religious
and you are in a ship

00:45:45.130 --> 00:45:49.830
that seems to break down.

00:45:49.830 --> 00:45:53.150
You pray. So they put a
carpet and they prayed.

00:45:53.150 --> 00:45:56.610
But there was another group who
believed that the maker was not

00:45:56.610 --> 00:45:59.110
in that direction but they
pray in the other direction.

00:45:59.110 --> 00:46:02.170
So, like 15 minutes instead

00:46:02.170 --> 00:46:05.040
